To normalize a vector, you need to divide each element of the vector by the magnitude of the vector. The magnitude of a vector is the length of the vector, which can be calculated using the Pythagorean theorem if the vector is in two dimensions, or the generalization of the Pythagorean theorem to higher dimensions if the vector is in three or more dimensions.
Here is an example of how to normalize a two-dimensional vector:
